p.note:
Lady Downshire wrote to JWC, 1 Feb.: “I hope that your ‘illness’ is all an excuse not to have an interview with poor Mr P!— I enclose a Cheque for the Balance of his Salary which pays him up to the 1st of March.” It seems that Plattnauer was suffering a recurrence of his mental health problems, and she did not want him in her household any more. Lady Downshire continued: “Lord George appears by his letter to me to be quite ready to receive him & there is no doubt it wd be the wisest move for Mr P if he would only go”; “Lord George” was presumably her husband’s uncle Lord George Hill (1801–79; see 24:73 TC to JAC, 18 June 1849
), in whose family Plattnauer had formerly been employed (see 24:159 TC to JAC, 2 Aug. 1849
). She then referred to four photographs arriving by post: “but the 3 Large ones he did not send, & I know nothing about them”; either photographs of Plattnauer or unidentified. For a photograph of Plattnauer, possibly taken around this time, in vol. 4 of JWC’s photograph albums, see opp. above.

div1.p:
Neuberg, Joseph (1806–67; see 11:231TC to JN, 21 Dec. 1839), a Jewish German businessman who had worked in Nottingham; naturalized British 1845, and retired from business 1849–56; m., 1841, Marian (d. 1848; see 23:77JWC to JN, 22 July 1848
). He was introduced to TC, whom he had long admired, by Ralph Waldo Emerson, 1848; helped TC as an unpaid sec., translated his work, and twice accompanied him on visits to Germany (1852 and 1858). From 1856–63 Neuberg lived at Oakley Villas, 25 (renumbered 140) Adelaide Rd., with his widowed sister, Rosetta (or Rosette) (ca. 1816–98)—who had m., ca. 1851, Adolph Frankau (1820–56; see 32:32TC to JN, [20 Nov. 1856]
)—and her two children, Frederick Joseph (b. 1854) and Gertrude Rosette Adolphine (b. ca. 1856). In 1863 he moved to Roslyn Park, Hampstead. After Frankau’s death, Neuberg managed Frankau’s company, which imported meerschaum pipes and fancy goods, at 25 Clements Lane, Lombard St., London.
